{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "Can a literary text ever have hidden depths? Are bad readings ever superficial? And is it ever helpful to talk this way? I'm going to suggest that the answer to all three questions is yes.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "That might seem like something so obvious as not to need saying, but in recent years people have started urging us to change our vocabulary, reducing or even eliminating our reliance on metaphors of depth.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "Superficially, everything seems pretty clear here: Darcy is an arrogant kind of person, and being reminded of Wickham-the 'mere' son of a steward-has only brought his haughtiness out more strongly.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "The reality, of course, is very different.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "Yes, Darcy is arrogant; that much is true. But when Elizabeth mentions Wickham, his changed expression has nothing to do with pride.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "Rather, he is thinking of the fact that this Wickham recently pursued his fifteen-year-old sister, angling for her money, and came within days of persuading her to elope with him.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "If the above interpretation is true, I hope it follows uncontroversially that there's a more and a less illuminating way to read the Austen sentence.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "The less illuminating way is to take it at face value, as a straightforward depiction of Darcy's emotional state; the more illuminating way is to see behind its subtle trickery and realize that Austen is setting a trap for us.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Now I see no reason not to call the less illuminating reading a superficial reading: the sentence superficially presents Darcy as getting even more puffed up than he was before but turns out, at a deeper level, to be working very differently.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "The text has hidden depths, and a reading that does not uncover them is itself a shallow one.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "Austen wants her readers to make a mistake, and then, ideally, go on to correct it.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "If they are to understand what's really going on, they have work to do.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "Austen, interestingly, doesn't do any of the work for us.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "When Darcy finally tells Elizabeth what happened between Wickham and his sister, Austen does not have Darcy add 'and that's why my face changed when you mentioned him to me-remember, back on page 63?'",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "Recognizing that Austen is setting traps for us like this-right from the famous first sentence, in fact-should nudge us in the direction of trying to figure out why.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "Perhaps it's supposed to chip away at our self-assurance, via the very process of reading.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "Perhaps it's supposed to help us turn ourselves into more discerning and careful readers-not just of novels but also of the world.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "Depth is multifarious; it is often deliberate; it is frequently salutary; and there is nothing wrong, it seems to me, with calling it by its name.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "Understanding the hauteur passage in Pride and Prejudice doesn't just clear up a local mystery about Darcy's frame of mind; it encourages us to think completely differently about the way in which the novel works, the nature of our reading experience, and what the entire enterprise is for.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "Our encounters with texts like those above-enigmatic texts, ironic texts, and the like-are encounters in which our initial understanding is not just mistaken but radically mistaken.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU21": {
      "text": "The text before us becomes a new kind of object, requiring a new set of operations, offering a new set of experiences, designed to have a whole new function.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU22": {
      "text": "Reading a novel with hidden depths is not like scanning a landscape, or turning an object around in our hands, or opening the curtains wider to get a better view.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU23": {
      "text": "Rather, it's like seeing a magician pull a rabbit out of a hat, or feeling the ground falling out from beneath our feet, or staring as the good guy rips off a mask to reveal a villainous face underneath.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU24": {
      "text": "It's not just that we didn't see the whole picture; it's that we got the key points totally wrong.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU25": {
      "text": "Artworks frequently contain features that are hidden.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU26": {
      "text": "These features are in no way limited to 'meanings,' but include things like secret complexities and non-obvious intended effects.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU27": {
      "text": "Many such features are there intentionally, having been deliberately introduced by the author.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU28": {
      "text": "Accordingly, one can read for depth without being a suspicious or symptomatic hermeneut.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
